JOHANNESBURG – MTN’s first quarter service revenue increased by 9,1 percent year on year despite its subscriber numbers declining in some key markets. The spike in revenue was largely driven by strong growth in Nigeria and Ghana. However, the group’s total subscriber numbers had declined by 6,6 percent to 221-million at the end of March. READ: MTN expands operations in South Sudan Africa’s biggest telecommunications firm says it invested R1,7-billion in capital expenditure during the quarter, following an improvement in its network last year. MTN says its mobile money services which grew by over 50-percent in the period is an area of massive potential for the group. eNCA